%N A238238 Decimal expansion of the polar angle, in radians, of a cone which makes a golden-ratio cut of the full solid angle.
%C A238238 The polar angle (or apex angle) of a cone which cuts a fraction f of the full solid angle (i.e., subtends a solid angle of 4*Pi*f steradians) is given by arccos(1-2*f). For a golden cut of the sphere surface by a cone with apex in its center, set f = 1-1/phi, phi being the golden ratio A001622. This value is in radians, its equivalent in degrees is A238239.
%C A238238 The apex angle of the isosceles triangle of smallest perimeter which circumscribes a semicircle (DeTemple, 1992). - _Amiram Eldar_, Jan 22 2022
%H A238238 Stanislav Sykora, <a href="/A238238/b238238.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..2000</a>
%H A238238 Duane W. DeTemple, <a href="https://www.fq.math.ca/Scanned/30-3/detemple.pdf">The Triangle of Smallest Perimeter which Circumscribes a Semicircle</a>, The Fibonacci Quarterly, Vol. 30, No. 3 (1992), p. 274.
%H A238238 Wikipedia, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_angle">Solid angle</a>.
%F A238238 arccos(1-2*(1-1/phi)) = arccos(2/phi-1), with phi = A001622.
